http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Tue 9 Jun 2015
Source: Chicago Tribune [edited]
http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-woman-with-rare-tb-form-was-treated-in-mchenry-county-20150608-story.html


Rare TB form [was] diagnosed in woman from India who traveled to McHenry County [Illinois].

A woman with a rare, hard-to-treat form of tuberculosis visited family in McHenry County after arriving at O'Hare International Airport in April [2015], and also traveled in Missouri and Tennessee, according to health officials who are trying to track down people who came in close contact with her.

The woman sought treatment at an undisclosed hospital in the Chicago [Illinois] area, where she was admitted to an isolation unit, and then was transferred to a National Institutes of Health hospital in Bethesda, Maryland. Her condition was reported as stable.

The woman has an extremely [extensively] drug-resistant form of the disease called XDR TB, which is impervious to most TB drugs. 3 to 4 cases are reported each year in the United States, on average.

TB is not as easily spread as diseases like the flu or measles. But it is a dangerous illness, especially for people with weakened immune systems, and health officials are taking the situation seriously, Skinner said.

Health officials in Illinois are working with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention [CDC] to find people with whom the woman may have had prolonged direct contact, in close quarters, according to CDC spokesman Tom Skinner. Debra Quackenbush, a spokeswoman for the McHenry County Health Department, said some of the people who came into close contact with the woman have been interviewed and are being monitored. She did not believe the general public was at risk.

Tuberculosis is caused by bacteria spread from person to person through the air. It usually affects the lungs and can lead to symptoms such as chest pain and coughing up blood. TB has been declining in the United States. But globally, each year it sickens about 9 million people and is a cause of 1.5 million deaths.

[Byline: Jasper Craven]

