[2]
Date: Tue 9 Jun 2015
Source: The Tennessean [edited]
http://www.tennessean.com/story/news/health/2015/06/09/woman-with-drug-resistant-tb-traveled-through-tennessee/28732039/


An Indian woman with a rare, drug-resistant form of tuberculosis traveled through Middle Tennessee during her recent visit to the US, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention [CDC]. The CDC is now working to identify individuals who may have been exposed.

The CDC released a statement Monday [8 Jun 2015] that said the woman traveled from India to Chicago [Illinois] in April, and after arriving in Chicago, she traveled in Missouri and Tennessee.

The woman then returned to Chicago and received treatment at a hospital where she was diagnosed with extensively drug-resistant tuberculosis, or XDR TB. She was then transported by air and ambulance to the National Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Maryland, where she is now in a respiratory isolation room.

According to the CDC, because XDR TB is multidrug resistant, many usual TB treatments are ineffective. "Because XDR TB is resistant to the most powerful 1st-line and 2nd-line drugs, patients are left with treatment options that are much less effective and often have worse treatment outcomes," according to the CDC website. The risk of acquiring XDR TB in the US is usually relatively low, but the CDC noted the disease can spread with ease.

The CDC will obtain a flight manifest and notify passengers who traveled with the woman and is working with the Illinois health department to trace potential contacts.

At this time, the woman has not been identified.

The Tennessee Department of Health has been advised of the woman's visit to Middle Tennessee and has been involved in the investigation to determine whether she was infectious during her visit and with whom she was in close contact, according to the department's Director of Communications and Media Relations Woody McMillin. McMillin said Tuesday afternoon [9 Jun 2015] that to his knowledge the woman did not pass through Nashville [Tennessee] and that she traveled to the state by car.

"Public health is always a priority for us," McMillin said of the state health department. "It's probably among our more important roles. In the case of a communicable disease, we use contact tracing to identify people who might have been exposed to an illness or disease to determine if they need to come in for testing."

TB germs are spread through the air when one person with TB disease of the lungs or throat coughs, sneezes, speaks or sings, according to the CDC, and people nearby breathe in the bacteria and become infected.

